00:37:08,919 --> 00:37:12,181
Well, you.

481
00:37:12,252 --> 00:37:16,411
I guess I was the last generation
of women who actually did that.

482
00:37:16,485 --> 00:37:20,247
It never even occurred to me
to get a divorce.

483
00:37:20,318 --> 00:37:24,341
I was so relieved when he died.

484
00:37:24,418 --> 00:37:29,749
- Don't hold anything back, Mom.
- Mmm.

485
00:37:29,819 --> 00:37:33,774
Ah, I like this
new spirit of frankness.

486
00:37:33,852 --> 00:37:36,409
It's oddly cleansing.

487
00:37:47,251 --> 00:37:49,911
I want to know
what you're like away from me here.

488
00:37:49,985 --> 00:37:54,145
That can't happen. The fact that you and
I aren't involved beyond this room...

489
00:37:54,218 --> 00:37:56,548
is what-- ahh-- appeals to me.

490
00:37:56,618 --> 00:38:00,607
You know how to play
your role damn well.

491
00:38:00,684 --> 00:38:03,378
Guilty as charged.

492
00:38:12,118 --> 00:38:16,380
- Roger, what do you want?
- I don't want much.

493
00:38:16,452 --> 00:38:19,577
I just want more of you.

494
00:38:21,618 --> 00:38:23,549
I can't give you that.

495
00:38:26,152 --> 00:38:29,776
Roger.
Don't be an anger ball.

496
00:38:29,851 --> 00:38:31,783
"An anger ball"?

497
00:38:33,385 --> 00:38:36,782
Don't you see?
What's great about you and me...

498
00:38:36,851 --> 00:38:41,682
right here, this very moment,
is that we don't come through
that door with a lot of baggage.

499
00:38:41,751 --> 00:38:45,513
We don't come through that door
with any baggage at all.

500
00:38:45,584 --> 00:38:49,540
And aren't we lucky?
We don't bring anything in...

501
00:38:49,617 --> 00:38:52,913
and we don't take anything out.

502
00:38:58,717 --> 00:39:08,480
%

503
00:39:08,551 --> 00:39:11,245
You're not the only one
who can dance alone.

504
00:39:11,317 --> 00:39:15,249
- What?
- I said you look like
a man in need of a Coke.

505
00:39:19,417 --> 00:39:22,111
%

506
00:39:24,951 --> 00:39:28,247
Uh, my friend here will have a Coke,
and I'll have a--

507
00:39:28,317 --> 00:39:32,011
Vodka martini,
very dry, three olives.

508
00:39:32,084 --> 00:39:34,016
Good memory.

509
00:39:34,084 --> 00:39:37,243
My mind has an endless capacity
for useless information.

510
00:39:39,750 --> 00:39:42,410
I've had a terrible day.

511
00:39:42,484 --> 00:39:45,848
I know we were talking about you for
a moment there, but my day was so bad.

512
00:39:45,917 --> 00:39:48,383
"How bad was it?" you might ask.

513
00:39:48,451 --> 00:39:51,473
-l might if you gave me the opportunity.
-l was saving you the effort...

514
00:39:51,551 --> 00:39:54,483
so that after I tell you my tale of woe
we can move on to happier topics.

515
00:39:54,551 --> 00:39:58,313
Perhaps one of your choosing. Anyway,
I'm an actress. Did I tell you that?

516
00:39:58,384 --> 00:40:02,749
- No. But I'm not surprised.
- I had this monologue in class today.

517
00:40:02,818 --> 00:40:06,476
And I was prepared.
You know, I mean, like really prepared.

518
00:40:06,551 --> 00:40:08,880
You know Suddenly Last Summer
by Tennessee Williams?

519
00:40:08,950 --> 00:40:12,575
- No.
- Oh, it's one of my favorites.
Great story.

520
00:40:12,650 --> 00:40:15,344
It's about this girl, Katherine-- moi--

521
00:40:15,417 --> 00:40:19,144
who is slated for a lobotomy
because the mother of her cousin
wants to keep her mouth shut...

522
00:40:19,217 --> 00:40:22,614
about certain goings-on involving
the old lady's son Sebastian.

523
00:40:22,683 --> 00:40:26,809
You see, the women sort of pimp
for Cousin Sebastian.
Are you following this?

524
00:40:26,883 --> 00:40:28,678
- Amazingly, yes.
- Anyway, it turns out...

525
00:40:28,750 --> 00:40:32,842
on their travels together Cousin
Sebastian liked to troll the beaches...

526
00:40:32,917 --> 00:40:37,373
looking for young native boys
in order to satisfy his base instincts.

527
00:40:37,451 --> 00:40:40,177
One hot afternoon in Cartagena...

528
00:40:40,250 --> 00:40:43,909
the boys decide they have had quite
enough of Sebastian's shenanigans...

529
00:40:43,983 --> 00:40:47,416
and they--
well, they eat him.

530
00:40:47,483 --> 00:40:51,006
- You mean metaphorically.
- No. They really eat him.

531
00:40:51,083 --> 00:40:55,742
They devour him.
In short, he's lunch.

532
00:40:55,817 --> 00:40:58,681
And Katherine witnesses
every course...

533
00:40:58,750 --> 00:41:01,080
from soup to nuts.

534
00:41:01,150 --> 00:41:03,377
If you'll pardon the expression.

535
00:41:03,450 --> 00:41:06,974
Anyway, I'm about to do
this killer monologue. I'm up next--

536
00:41:07,050 --> 00:41:10,607
If one more actor saunters
into this class...

537
00:41:10,683 --> 00:41:15,479
and recites Katherine's "native boys
ate my cousin Sebastian" speech...

538
00:41:15,550 --> 00:41:17,743
from Suddenly Last Summer...

539
00:41:17,817 --> 00:41:20,681
I am going to puke.

540
00:41:20,750 --> 00:41:24,113
Now, who is up next?

541
00:41:25,450 --> 00:41:29,439
Um... Joan! You're on.

542
00:41:30,916 --> 00:41:34,576
The teacher didn't lose
his lunch. I did.

543
00:41:35,650 --> 00:41:38,411
- I'm sorry.
- So am l.

544
00:41:41,283 --> 00:41:45,443
Now, on to happier topics, I promise.
How about a movie?

545
00:41:45,515 --> 00:41:47,345
- I told you.
- I know.

546
00:41:47,416 --> 00:41:50,246
I know. You don't date.
Is it a religious thing?

547
00:41:50,316 --> 00:41:54,373
- No.
- Well, you like movies, don't you?

548
00:41:54,450 --> 00:41:56,381
- They're okay.
- How about tomorrow night?

549
00:41:56,450 --> 00:41:59,245
It doesn't have to be a date.
We'll meet at the theater.

550
00:42:00,949 --> 00:42:04,574
- I don't know.
- Look. I'll make it easy.
Okay, blue boy?

551
00:42:04,649 --> 00:42:08,479
Tomorrow night I'm going to the
late show of the Texas Chainsaw Massacre
at the Sunset Five.

552
00:42:08,550 --> 00:42:11,482
If you decide you would like to
join the human race, meet me there.

553
00:42:16,949 --> 00:42:21,278
Uh, now, in other news, they found
a cure for cancer. Okay. Uh, moving on.

554
00:42:21,348 --> 00:42:24,473
- No, they--
- Do you ever hear from Wendy?

555
00:42:24,549 --> 00:42:28,141
What on Earth made you think of Wendy?

556
00:42:28,216 --> 00:42:32,807
- Oh, I don't know.
Just thinking about the old days.
- Yes.

557
00:42:32,882 --> 00:42:35,280
Very old. Ancient.

558
00:42:36,916 --> 00:42:41,712
Well, do you?
Do you ever hear from her?

559
00:42:41,781 --> 00:42:43,714
Any reason I should?

560
00:42:43,782 --> 00:42:47,306
Any reason you should keep
her picture in your desk?

561
00:42:50,183 --> 00:42:54,410
None that you should
concern yourself with.

562
00:42:54,482 --> 00:42:59,107
Viagra. Oh, God.

563
00:42:59,182 --> 00:43:03,047
Viagra. That's what everyone's
talking about. Are you on it yet?

564
00:43:03,116 --> 00:43:05,274
Just the men.
Okay, uh, well...

565
00:43:05,348 --> 00:43:07,575
it's so successful,
you know, of course--

566
00:43:17,948 --> 00:43:19,880
- Hey. I made it.
- Hi.

567
00:43:19,948 --> 00:43:24,074
- Uh, casually attired.
- Wow.

568
00:43:24,148 --> 00:43:26,580
Yeah, I know. The flowers are
a little much, and I'm late.

569
00:43:26,648 --> 00:43:28,773
But only because I had second thoughts
about the flowers...

570
00:43:28,849 --> 00:43:31,871
and I threw them away halfway down the
block, and then I had third thoughts...

571
00:43:31,948 --> 00:43:33,971
and went back and got them.

572
00:43:34,048 --> 00:43:36,309
Well, I'm glad you did.

573
00:43:36,382 --> 00:43:38,677
Thank you.

574
00:43:38,748 --> 00:43:40,680
Come in.
Come in, come in, come in.

575
00:43:40,748 --> 00:43:44,874
- Thanks.
- l, uh-- I hope you like Italian.

576
00:43:44,948 --> 00:43:47,140
- I hope you like merlot.
- I do.

577
00:43:47,215 --> 00:43:49,237
Wow! That's a--

578
00:43:49,315 --> 00:43:51,246
- Barley.
- That's some dog! That's, uh--

579
00:43:51,314 --> 00:43:54,542
- Barley, get down, sweetie.
Come on. Come on.
- Whoa.

580
00:43:54,614 --> 00:43:57,240
- My family has a thing for pets.
- Yeah. Oh.

581
00:43:57,315 --> 00:43:59,780
That's, uh--
That's certainly impressive.

582
00:43:59,848 --> 00:44:04,372
Suddenly I'm feeling
a little inadequate. That's--

583
00:44:05,448 --> 00:44:08,074
I, uh-- It's almost ready.
I, uh--

584
00:44:08,148 --> 00:44:12,807
Sorry that took me so long. I was
on the phone with one of my sisters.

585
00:44:14,114 --> 00:44:17,638
- The married one.
- The one who's having an affair?

586
00:44:17,714 --> 00:44:19,941
Yeah, well, the one
who's always having an affair.

587
00:44:20,014 --> 00:44:22,277
Her husband doesn't
suspect anything?

588
00:44:22,347 --> 00:44:25,973
Her husband is sweet,
but he's a bit dim.

589
00:44:27,514 --> 00:44:30,106
He doesn't have
much of an imagination.

590
00:44:30,182 --> 00:44:33,114
Chandler girls like their men
with imagination?

591
00:44:33,181 --> 00:44:35,477
Yeah. It helps.

592
00:44:36,815 --> 00:44:41,076
You know, I'm told
I have a good imagination.

593
00:44:43,081 --> 00:44:45,273
I don't want
to have sex tonight.

594
00:44:48,980 --> 00:44:52,310
- Okay.
- I mean if that's why you thought
I invited you over here--

595
00:44:52,381 --> 00:44:54,506
- I invited myself over here.
- Well, whatever.

596
00:44:54,580 --> 00:44:57,570
- I mean, I know that
must be kind of unusual.
- It's not unusual. l--

597
00:44:57,648 --> 00:44:59,579
I mean, I'm sure that most women
don't turn you down.

598
00:44:59,648 --> 00:45:02,045
Meredith, can we talk about
something else?

599
00:45:02,114 --> 00:45:04,740
Honestly, sex is the last thing
on my mind right now.

600
00:45:04,814 --> 00:45:07,042
- Okay, okay.
- Okay?

601
00:45:07,115 --> 00:45:10,274
Okay. Okay.

602
00:45:10,346 --> 00:45:13,904
Want a taste? I mean, l-I'm sorry
if I ruined your plans. That's all.

603
00:45:13,980 --> 00:45:16,912
I didn't have any plans!
I just think--

604
00:45:16,980 --> 00:45:19,412
You know, you've got
a few too many rules working for you...

605
00:45:19,480 --> 00:45:22,446
and way too many rules
workin' against me!

606
00:45:22,513 --> 00:45:25,707
I really like you, but--

607
00:45:25,780 --> 00:45:28,372
This kind of thing
is pissing me off.

608
00:45:31,780 --> 00:45:34,541
Maybe this wasn't such a good idea.

609
00:45:37,647 --> 00:45:40,772
I can't understand why you haven't had
a relationship lately.

610
00:45:43,780 --> 00:45:47,473
Really?
Well, that doesn't take long, does it?

611
00:45:47,548 --> 00:45:49,775
- What doesn't?
- I mean, you turn a guy down...

612
00:45:49,847 --> 00:45:52,972
a-and wham, he just metamorphoses
into an anger ball.

613
00:45:53,047 --> 00:45:55,205
- "Anger ball"?
- See?

614
00:45:55,280 --> 00:45:58,712
All I said was
I have a good imagination.

615
00:45:58,780 --> 00:46:01,973
- I wasn't talking about sex.
- Really.

616
00:46:02,046 --> 00:46:05,036
I've had enough... sex.

617
00:46:05,114 --> 00:46:07,045
Mostly with women
I didn't really like...

618
00:46:07,114 --> 00:46:10,375
a-and probably
didn't really like me.

619
00:46:12,879 --> 00:46:15,073
Call me nuts, man,
but l-- I like you.

620
00:46:15,146 --> 00:46:17,475
And...

621
00:46:17,547 --> 00:46:21,035
yeah, if something happens between us,
sex will probably enter into it.

622
00:46:21,113 --> 00:46:24,909
But not until you break
the brick wall down around yourself...

623
00:46:24,980 --> 00:46:28,310
and certainly not tonight.

624
00:46:31,280 --> 00:46:33,212
Are you finished?

625
00:46:34,313 --> 00:46:36,779
- Yeah.
- I'll show you out.

626
00:46:38,380 --> 00:46:41,937
- What!
- Look, this is exactly
what I don't want.

627
00:46:42,013 --> 00:46:43,911
- Somebody being straight with you?
- Yes!

628
00:46:43,979 --> 00:46:47,207
Yes, yes.

629
00:46:47,280 --> 00:46:51,803
You know what, Trent?
I do not have the stamina for this.

630
00:46:51,879 --> 00:46:53,811
I don't.

631
00:46:53,879 --> 00:46:56,811
- Meredith, we haven't
even started anything.
- You know what?

632
00:46:56,879 --> 00:47:00,539
We're not going to.

633
00:47:00,612 --> 00:47:04,272
Because let me just jump ahead
to the inevitable. Okay?

634
00:47:05,345 --> 00:47:07,278
We get together.

635
00:47:07,345 --> 00:47:10,311
You hurt me.
It ends badly.

636
00:47:10,380 --> 00:47:14,540
That's a really depressing way
to look at a fledgling relationship.

637
00:47:14,613 --> 00:47:17,976
Well, there's nothing
fledgling about it.

638
00:47:18,046 --> 00:47:20,944
And honestly, that is
the only viewpoint that I have.

639
00:47:23,913 --> 00:47:27,709
Then I feel sorry for you,
Meredith, because I didn't
come over here to hurt you.

640
00:47:33,346 --> 00:47:36,709
- I hope Barley likes Italian.
- He does.

641
00:47:51,345 --> 00:47:53,072
What?

642
00:48:04,878 --> 00:48:07,310
What are you watching?

643
00:48:07,379 --> 00:48:09,641
Midnight Lace.

644
00:48:09,712 --> 00:48:13,144
Ah. Doris Day.

645
00:48:13,212 --> 00:48:15,804
Oh, yeah. That's the one
where she thinks she's going crazy...

646
00:48:15,879 --> 00:48:18,571
but it's really her husband
that's driving her to suicide...

647
00:48:18,645 --> 00:48:20,634
for her money.

648
00:48:20,711 --> 00:48:23,234
Well, thank you, Paul!

649
00:48:23,312 --> 00:48:26,744
Why don't you just go-- go find
a theater that's showing Citizen Kane...

650
00:48:26,812 --> 00:48:29,403
and yell out
"Rosebud is a sled"?

651
00:48:29,479 --> 00:48:31,944
- I'm sorry.
I thought you'd seen it before.
- Well, I hadn't.

652
00:48:32,012 --> 00:48:34,375
I mean, I thought we'd seen it before.

653
00:48:34,445 --> 00:48:37,037
Perhaps you have me confused
with Wendy.

654
00:48:37,112 --> 00:48:39,043
So that's what this is all about.

655
00:48:39,112 --> 00:48:43,567
- What "this"? There isn't any "this."
- No? No "this"?

656
00:48:43,646 --> 00:48:45,702
Do you normally speak
through clenched teeth?

657
00:48:45,778 --> 00:48:48,608
I'm not speaking any different
than normal.

658
00:48:48,679 --> 00:48:51,236
- Differently.
- Oh!

659
00:49:02,208 --> 00:49:04,141
You are being idiotic.

660
00:49:04,209 --> 00:49:08,800
Well, you wouldn't want me to act
any different than normal, would you?

661
00:49:08,875 --> 00:49:12,238
- "Differently."
- This isn't exactly what I had in mind.

662
00:49:12,308 --> 00:49:14,796
- Do you still see her?
- Who?

663
00:49:14,875 --> 00:49:17,705
"Who?" Who?
Doris Day!

664
00:49:17,775 --> 00:49:20,298
Oh, you mean Wendy.

665
00:49:20,375 --> 00:49:22,967
You thought I didn't know,
didn't you?

666
00:49:23,041 --> 00:49:26,633
You think the little woman doesn't know
when her husband has an affair.

667
00:49:26,708 --> 00:49:31,367
Hannah, it was 25 years ago,
and it wasn't an affair.

668
00:49:31,442 --> 00:49:33,635
Oh, don't insult my intelligence.

669
00:49:33,708 --> 00:49:37,299
Your intelligence, at the moment,
is in serious doubt.

670
00:49:37,375 --> 00:49:40,136
- Screw you!
- Hannah.

671
00:49:40,208 --> 00:49:42,696
Paul.

672
00:49:49,042 --> 00:49:53,303
Do you really want
to talk about this? Hmm?

673
00:49:53,375 --> 00:49:58,568
Because if you do, I'll tell you
everything you want to know.

674
00:49:58,642 --> 00:50:01,574
You might start
by being honest with me.

675
00:50:01,642 --> 00:50:04,437
- It wasn't an affair?
- It wasn't.

676
00:50:04,508 --> 00:50:09,099
- I never slept with Wendy.
- Oh, please!

677
00:50:09,175 --> 00:50:11,573
Hey, calm down.
You're overwrought.

678
00:50:11,642 --> 00:50:13,903
I am perfectly wrought.

679
00:50:13,974 --> 00:50:17,065
Given the circumstances,
I'm even a bit underwrought.

680
00:50:17,141 --> 00:50:19,902
- There's no such word.
- There is now.

681
00:50:21,808 --> 00:50:25,740
Do you want to know...
why I didn't sleep with Wendy?

682
00:50:31,841 --> 00:50:34,932
I am, as they say, all ears.

683
00:50:35,008 --> 00:50:38,440
Well, I never
slept with Wendy...

684
00:50:38,507 --> 00:50:41,497
because I was
too much in love with her.

685
00:50:43,907 --> 00:50:45,840
Oh.

686
00:50:50,674 --> 00:50:53,867
You couldn't have died
without telling me that?

687
00:51:07,607 --> 00:51:09,869
Keenan? You going out?

688
00:51:09,941 --> 00:51:13,532
Yes, Dad.

689
00:51:17,940 --> 00:51:20,702
Hi. I know for this technically
not to be a date...

690
00:51:20,774 --> 00:51:24,206
we should have gone dutch, but the
tickets were selling out so fast, so--

691
00:51:24,274 --> 00:51:27,297
What would you have done
if I didn't show up?

692
00:51:27,374 --> 00:51:29,863
Um, well, after I recovered from
the supreme disappointment...

693
00:51:29,940 --> 00:51:32,532
and picked up the pieces
of my fractured ego...

694
00:51:32,606 --> 00:51:36,368
I would have run down the escalator and
invited the guy standing on the corner.

695
00:51:36,441 --> 00:51:38,373
You know, the one holding the sign.

696
00:51:38,440 --> 00:51:41,033
The one that says,
"Will work for food"?

697
00:51:41,107 --> 00:51:44,369
Or a movie.
You should have read the fine print.

698
00:51:47,774 --> 00:51:50,534
% I'll plant my own tree %

699
00:51:50,607 --> 00:51:54,299
% And I'll make it grow %

700
00:51:54,374 --> 00:51:57,135
% My tree will not be %

701
00:51:57,206 --> 00:52:01,105
% Just one in a row %

702
00:52:01,174 --> 00:52:04,140
% My tree will offer shade %

703
00:52:04,206 --> 00:52:08,003
% When strangers go by %

704
00:52:08,072 --> 00:52:10,301
% If you're a stranger %

705
00:52:10,373 --> 00:52:12,635
% Brother, well, so am I %

706
00:52:12,706 --> 00:52:14,672
Gin gimlet, rocks.

707
00:52:14,741 --> 00:52:16,672
Make it two.

708
00:52:16,740 --> 00:52:18,797
- I'm Lana.
- Hugh.

709
00:52:18,872 --> 00:52:21,498
I haven't seen you here before.

710
00:52:21,573 --> 00:52:25,301
- Well, how do you know that?
- Honey, you sounded
like John Wayne in a bathhouse.

711
00:52:25,373 --> 00:52:28,305
Well, as a matter of fact,
this is my first time here.

712
00:52:28,373 --> 00:52:31,635
I'm 28 years old,
in case you're wondering.

